Key audit matters

How the matter was addressed in the audit

Impairment assessment of plant and equipment used in medical devices segment (Refer to note 11 to the financial statements)

As at July 31, 2017, the Group’s carrying value of total property, plant and equipment (“PPE”) amounted to $17,488,000, of which $8,480,000 relates to the medical devices segment.

Management has identified the cash-generating unit (“CGU”) of the medical devices segment and has concluded that all the subsidiaries in the medical devices segment in aggregate represent the lowest level of CGU in the medical devices segment.

As the medical devices segment continues to incur a loss for the year ended July 31, 2017, there is a risk that the recoverable value of the PPE used in the medical devices segment may be lower than its carrying value requiring an lmpalrment Charge to be recorded against those assets. The impairment assessment process involves slgnificaht management’s judgement and estimates m determining the key assumptions in the valueeineuse (”VIU”).

The key assumptions made by management in determining the VIU include, amongst others, the revenue growth rates, gross operating margins, working capital changes, discount rates and terminal growth rates.

We obtained an understanding of the management’s relevant control around the valuation methodology and valuation model by performing walk-through of the relevant control

We checked management's valuation model for arithmetic accuracy,

We evaluated management’s basis of determining all subsidiaries in the medical devices segment as one CGU.

We evaluated and challenged the key assumptions including those related to future cash flow forecast, such as revenue growth rates, gross operating margins, working capital changes, discount rates and termlnal growth rates.

We also engaged our valuation specialist to review the reasonableness of the discount rate used in determinlng the VIU.

We assessed the reliability of management’s estimates by comparing the historical financial performance of the medical devices segment CGU against the budget.

We also performed a sensitivity analysis around the key drivers to the future cash flow forecast, being the revenue growth rates, the gross operating margins and the discount rates.

We have also assessed the appropriateness of the dlsclosures included in note 3 and note 11 to the financial statements in relation to the key sources of estimation uncertainty and the key assumptions used.
